1D<ue5>4D<ue5>MAMMOGRAMS<ql>
<styl>by <m2>By <m1> <m0>DOLORES KONG<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0> Boston Globe Service<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>   The National Cancer Institute plans to reconsider its controversial stand against routine screening for breast cancer for women under 50, after a new international analysis produced compelling evidence that the screening saves lives.<ep>
   The yet-unpublished new report, by Swedish researchers who analyzed earlier studies involving more than 150,000 women, found a 24 percent lower death rate among women who got mammograms beginning in their 40s.<ep>
   ``It was a little bit of a surprise to people that as much as a 24 percent decrease in mortality was demonstrated,'' said Dr. Laszlo Tabar, director of mammography at Falun Central Hospital in Sweden, who presented the analysis several weeks ago to 210 scientists from 16 countries, including the United States.<ep>
   ``Breast cancer is not forgiving in the age group of 40 to 49,'' Tabar said, with the latest results suggesting that breast cancer in younger women is a faster-spreading disease than in older ones. ``If you miss once, there's not another chance.''<ep>
   <m2><ql>
